This is the critical finding. The candidate's core claim is now confirmed/refuted by this code:

```cpp
template <typename T>
void convert(std::vector<T>& value) {
  if (!write) value.clear();          // clears Q

  uint32_t count = (uint32_t)value.size();   // count = 0 after clear!
  convert_len(count);                  // reads attacker count m into count

  if (!write) {
    if (count > MAX_CONTAINER_ELEMENTS) { set_error(); return; }
    value.resize(count);               // resizes Q to attacker m
  }
  ...
}
```

So on the deserialization path, `convert(std::vector<ecc_point_t>& Q)` DOES indeed `clear()` then `resize(count)` where `count` is read from the wire (attacker-controlled, bounded only by `MAX_CONTAINER_ELEMENTS = 1<<20`).

Now the candidate's claim about the pre-check in `ec_pve_batch_t::convert`:

```cpp
void convert(coinbase::converter_t& converter) {
  if (int(Q.size()) != n) {       // Q.size() == n here (constructor resized), so check passes (no-op on deser)
    converter.set_error();
    return;
  }
  converter.convert(Q, L, b);     // this clears+resizes Q to attacker count m
  ...
}
```

The candidate correctly observes the pre-check `Q.size() != n` is checked BEFORE the convert modifies Q, so it's a no-op for catching a mismatch after deserialization. After `convert(Q,...)`, `Q.size()` becomes the attacker's `m`.

Now I need to trace the actual decrypt path very carefully to verify whether there's a re-validation of `Q.size() == n` anywhere. Let me read the api implementation `pve_batch_single_recipient.cpp` and `parse_batch_ciphertext`.

